00:00:00.659 --> 00:00:02.190
Are you training your abs enough?

00:00:02.190 --> 00:00:07.910
Even if you told me you did them 7 days a
week, my answer to you would be no.

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:10.540
Let me explain in today's video.

00:00:10.540 --> 00:00:15.509
What's up guys?

00:00:15.509 --> 00:00:20.480
Jeff Cavaliere, ATHLEANX.COM.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:21.480
Ab training.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:22.480
How much is too much?

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:26.560
Well, if you've seen any of my videos here
on our channel, you know I'm going on record

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:32.490
to say that I believe 5, 6, or even 7 times
a week ab training is great.

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:33.490
Why?

00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:37.059
Because these resilient, postural muscles
are built for that.

00:00:37.059 --> 00:00:41.020
These guys are ready to take on the work,
and the more frequent the work, the better.

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:45.340
Now, that goes contrary to pretty much everything
else I believe when it comes to training.

00:00:45.340 --> 00:00:50.430
We have a very specific dose that muscles
can handle that beyond that, we wind up overtraining

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:51.850
and causing damage.

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:57.130
The abs, because of their ever-constant firing
throughout the day, these muscles are different

00:00:57.130 --> 00:00:59.289
and built for more volume.

00:00:59.289 --> 00:01:02.309
That said, is that all you need to do, right,
5, 6, 7 days a week?

00:01:02.309 --> 00:01:03.309
No.

00:01:03.309 --> 00:01:07.540
Of course, you obviously need to have your
nutrition in place because even the best ab

00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:10.600
program with the shittiest diet leaves you
with the shittiest abs.

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:11.600
Ok.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:13.090
There's just no way around it.

00:01:13.090 --> 00:01:14.580
But, there's more than that.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:19.400
We talk about direct ab training, and then
indirect ab training.

00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:23.690
And for anybody that's familiar with ATHLEANX,
you should know all about the core being at

00:01:23.690 --> 00:01:25.970
the core of every single exercise that we
do.

00:01:25.970 --> 00:01:29.990
So, what I want today to do was to show you,
what about abs?

00:01:29.990 --> 00:01:35.800
Could we have a workout where we highly target
the abs and work them on every single thing

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:38.330
we're doing, but we're not even directly training
them?

00:01:38.330 --> 00:01:43.250
So, let me go right down, muscle group by
muscle group, an example exercise that's going

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:47.980
to highly integrate the abs without us feeling
as if we are training the abs directly.

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:52.520
You add those two together, indirect and direct
ab training, you've got a pretty powerful

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:54.470
combo.

00:01:54.470 --> 00:01:56.230
Ok so let's start right off the top.

00:01:56.230 --> 00:01:57.230
Chest.

00:01:57.230 --> 00:01:58.230
Right.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.030
We take a Single Arm Dumbbell Bench Press.

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:03.000
As you can see, when I demonstrate this exercise,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.520
if I have a dumbbell in one single hand and
I lower it down to that side, obviously, 60,

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:12.110
70, 80 pounds, that's all pulling in that
one direction.

00:02:12.110 --> 00:02:18.950
So there's a lot of demand on my core to pull
myself back, keep my trunk from rotating in

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:21.110
the same direction that dumbbell is dropping.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:25.030
If you want to make this extra challenging,
you want to make it a little less of a chest

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:28.660
exercise, then lift the leg on the same side
as the dumbbell.

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:33.360
And that's going to make it even harder for
you to resist the rotation.

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:34.440
Next we look at back.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.730
Alright the king of all back exercises, the
Pull Ups.

00:02:37.730 --> 00:02:41.890
But as you see with this one slight modification
of the exercise that I'm doing here,

00:02:41.890 --> 00:02:46.270
the knees come up, we get a tremendous amount
of core activity.

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:50.600
Matter of fact, we stress the lower abs which
is even better because these are even harder

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:51.810
for us guys to target.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:54.060
Now, how do I know this?

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:57.970
Because, as you guys might remember, if you've
been watching me for any length of time.

00:02:57.970 --> 00:03:01.930
Having a hernia surgery, I went through and
tried to do my recovery and speed it up as

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:02.930
fast as possible.

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:07.500
I was down on the ground doing crunches, literally
three days later,

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:11.900
but for three weeks, I couldn't even suspend
myself off of a pull up bar.

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:12.900
Why?

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:14.370
Because it is one of the most demanding core
exercises.

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:19.120
As soon as you lift your feet off the ground
while hanging from a bar, you already ignite

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:20.120
those abs.

00:03:20.120 --> 00:03:24.710
So yet another way just by pulling your knees
up, to really engage the abs, at the same

00:03:24.710 --> 00:03:27.930
time, you're getting that old classic killer
back exercise going.

00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:31.480
The next one I demonstrate here is for the
shoulders.

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:34.110
Our Seated Long Leg Press.

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:38.120
We all know, pressing overhead, tough activity.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:42.090
Even harder when we're on the ground right,
and on our butts.

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:45.819
Because when we get our legs out in front
of us, we're really taking away any of the

00:03:45.819 --> 00:03:48.650
leverage that we once had with our legs underneath
us.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:53.560
Now normally guys, I want you on your feet
for every exercise that you do, because that's

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:57.900
being athletic; however, in this case, we're
going after a different target here.

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:03.060
